1sl.title: Arbital: 10x better than Wikipedia
1sl.clickbait: What significant improvements does Arbital have over Wikipedia?
1sl.text:
Wikipedia has done many things right, and we can learn from its history to create a better platform. Let's take a look at a some of the problems Wikipedia has today and how Arbital is going to resolve them.

### Learning

Wikipedia built its technology and set up its policies to recreate the experience of an encyclopedia, but online. An encyclopedia is great for getting information about a subject, but it's close to useless when it comes to actually learning. Wikipedia occasionally attempts to solve that problem by creating additional pages, e.g. [Introduction to general relativity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introduction_to_general_relativity), but this approach will not scale because this problem is rather difficult. Arbital's solution to this is a [1ln network of requisites], which allow the platform to dynamically create [1rt sequences of pages] tailored to each user, where each page itself also adjusts to user's preferences and knowledge.

### Granularity

Wikipedia doesn't allow (and will actively delete) content that they think its not [notable](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Notability). This often leads to creation of other wiki communities, which specialize in their particular area, e.g. [World of Warcraft wiki](http://wowwiki.wikia.com/wiki/Portal:Main). On Arbital, we want to embrace all content and communities. The most interesting things in research, entertainment, and most other areas are often at the edges, where a small minority (or ~5M people, in the case of WoW) care about that information deeply.

In case of science, this problem is even worse. Wikipedia also doesn't allow [original research](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research), but if you are a scientist, original research is the most interesting part. And all settled science was some point uncertain. By not allowing that kind of content on its platform, Wikipedia is falling increasingly behind the rapidly accelerating scientific frontier.

### Truth vs neutrality

Wikipedia's official policy is ["Verifiability, not truth."](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability,_not_truth) On Arbital, we think [9c truth] is pretty great, and we should have more of it. We even have a [1r8 guiding principle] for how to find it. Verifiability works pretty well for figuring out the population of a country, but it's useless when it comes to controversial, unsettled topics.

### Expertise

Wikipedia has the notion of a [reliable source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Reliable_sources), but no method for tracking expertise within the system. This often results in bitter edit wars, which are usually resolved by a person with limited domain expertise. Arbital is planning to solve this problem with [14s karma] and [14r dominion].

### Getting answers

When was the last time you tried to research something on Wikipedia that wasn't a settled fact? Perhaps you were wondering if you should supplement your diet with Vitamin D. Did you get a satisfying answer? Probably not. Wikipedia is good at providing the reader with a ton of information, but it's not good at answering questions, and it's even worse at quickly giving an accurate overview for a disputed topic. Compare this to your experience on [StackOverflow](http://stackoverflow.com/), where it's much easier to tell what the best answer is. Arbital has many features that make finding the right answer quick and easy: [3r vote bars], [3p likes], [17g comments], instant search, and a beta version of [185 questions] and [187 answers]. Arbital also let's you know how much confidence you should have about the information, and allows you to dive deeper into discussion if you want to understand the current state of the topic better.

### Etc...

You can take a look at all the other things [Wikipedia is not](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:What_Wikipedia_is_not). Some of those decisions make sense, but others restrict Wikipedia from becoming all it could be.
